ourse, it also seems that every new server is going to be the &quot;Roleplay server&quot; which lasts until people get bored playing a newbie and go back to their main and their friends on their main server.<br><br>Herpes Simplex,<br>Mage, Thrice bless by Bertoxxulous <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/utikkoklock.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tikk OKlock</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>newbie</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/24/01 2:19:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hmmmm</span><hr size=1> History of the O'klock Family<br><br><br>Tale told by Tikk O’Klock, Minstrel of Tunare.<br><br><br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Told to me by many heroes, and passed down into this book, I now tell the story of my past, my brother, and the conflict we are drawn to fight.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp My father was a famous clockmaker from Qyenos. My mother… well… She was a free spirit.  A warrior of Tunare, she participated in the Great Wars of Ro, slaying many viscous followers of Innoruk.  I heard many tales of her bravery, although I never was able to see her fight in person.  Her name was Antha, and she was well respected among her fellow Emerald warriors.  She met my father by chance one foggy afternoon in the Eastern Plains of Karana.  My father was visiting a local town, selling some small clocks to the residents there.  He wandered outside and became lost, eventually arriving at the base of a waterfall… He sat down and began to fish, waiting for the fog to clear so he could return to Qyenos.  My mother was bathing in the river, and upon seeing him, swam deeper out, keeping a close eye on him.  He did not spot her right away, and began to sing an ole’ sea chanty to himself, casting his broken fishing rod into the river near her.  Eventually the water grew too cold for even a brave warrior, and she was forced to wade closer to shore.  She spoke to him in a whisper, and asked for her clothes…. *laughs* my father was even more embarrassed then her… He cautiously walked over to pick up her clothes, and dropped them near the shore.  He then apologized and began to shuffle away from the river. <br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp She caught up with him a bit later; I think it was near the great wooden bridge that separates the Karanas.  She said hello… and asked which direction he was headed.  I’m not sure if it mattered what he said, she would have followed him anywhere… They returned to Qyenos, and settled down for a year.  Tunare graced her with twins, thus my brother and I where born and anointed in the temple of Rodcet Nife.  I was named Tikk, and my brother Tokk.  My father took a liking to me… And my mother took a liking to my brother. He was raised as a warrior, and I as a bard… We both got into lots of trouble as small children, but I will not bore you with those tales at this point.  <br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Our lives changed during the Second War of Ro… Tunare called upon my mother in a dream, and asked her to return to combat.  At the age of 7, both my brother and I said goodbye to our mother for the last time.  She died in combat later on that year… My brother was given her sword, still stained with the blood of the many dark elves she had slain before her death.  I expressed my loss through song, while he grew stronger each day, traveling out into the countryside to take his aggression on Gnoll pups and smaller creatures.  One day, my brother did not return home for supper.  My father, although concerned, did not want to risk sending me out into the night to look for him.  I cried that night, thinking I was going to lose another family member.  When the sun rose the next morning, my brother still had not returned home.  I strapped on some torn leather armor, and went to the door of my home.  My father was sitting at the table, and could not even raise his eyes to watch me leave.  I suppose he feared that he would be alone for good after that day…<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I tracked my brother into Blackburrow, and tailed a group of adventurers deep into the dungeon.  Finally I heard some moans, and saw my brother lying on the floor near a lake, his leg broken.  I ran over to him, and helped him back to the Qyenos Hills.  He was tired, but still very emotionally withdrawn.  I began to scream, tears flowing from my eyes.  He grabbed my shirt, lifted me up and threw me into the ground.  He was much stronger then I, but with a broken leg, the odds where evened.  We pummeled each other for almost an hour, finally stopping to rest… He then laughed at me, and cursed Tunare… He began to cry out for our mother, and I put my arm on his shoulder.  We talked until the sun went down, about life, and us, our father, and the loss of our mother.  My father was overjoyed to see us alive, and for the remainder of our childhood, we where given anything material our hearts desired.  My brother and I began to fight together, using the rhythm of my drum, with the power of his sword.  When we turned 16, our father sent us to the Land of the Elves… The great tree city of Felwithe.  There we trained for 3 years, my brother in the former guild of Antha, and I… I just sang… I kept alive the memory of my mother, and entertained the elven ladies on the side. <br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Three weeks ago everything changed.  I was awakened by the sound of commotion… I later found out the gods of Norrath had declared war upon each other.  Many Elven bards choose to follow the warlord Rallos Zek, and I lost many dear friends.  Luckily for us, Tunare and Rodcet Nife choose to ally, thus throwing us upon the side of good.  We received a letter from Qyenos last night.  It told us of a surprise Erudite attack on Qyenos.  Our father was dead… He ship destroyed in naval battle off the small Isle of Kerra.  <br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp We are both worn, even at the tender age of 19, we know what is war.  We know of loss, of pain, of death, and most important, we know of Life.  We are fighting this war, not behind the ranks, but at the forefront.  Every time we spill the blood of evil, we shall rejoice.  I am Tikk O’Klock, and this is my tale.  Pray to your pagan gods that you do not meet my brother and I on the battlefield.  Mercy if not for the just, but for the weak.<br><br> <br> <p>Tikk O'Klock<BR>Half-Elf :: Bard :: Tunare<BR>Divinity</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/udikafu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dikafu</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/16/01 5:05:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.loftinspace.com.au/image/Daisaku3.gif border=0 width=32 height=32></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hmmmm</span><hr size=1> I have read a lot of EQ RP stories. This is by far the best. Thank you Tikk<br><br>/clap<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showPrevMessage?topicID=5.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showNextMessage?topicID=5.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=18><img src=http://home.att.net/~neoleo/reply2.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a